  "scientific_question": "BRAF V600E melanoma is the ideal single-driver system to test whether ODS topology predicts drug efficacy OR whether driver mutation addiction overrides structural topology. SURPRISE: Perturbation loop shows BRAF is a structural ANCHOR (delta_r=-0.0655), not a damper as initially hypothesized. MEK1 and ERK1 are the strongest anchors (-0.2253, -0.2442 respectively). CDK4 (+0.2342) and TP53 (+0.2594) are the largest dampers. After applying standard exclusions (CDK4/6 cytostatic CLASS5, BET/JQ1 potency gap CLASS4, MDM2 TP53-WT gating required), the testable nodes are: AKT1(+0.1263), PI3K(+0.0900) as dampers vs MEK1(-0.2253), mTOR(-0.1096), BRAF(-0.0655) as anchors. ODS predicts damper drugs (AKT1, PI3K) should outperform anchor drugs (MEK1, mTOR, BRAF) in cell killing. But BRAF V600E is the driver mutation -- vemurafenib/dabrafenib target BRAF V600E directly. If BRAF inhibitors kill more than AKT1 inhibitors despite BRAF being a structural anchor, this establishes the \"driver addiction override\" as a new mechanism class (CLASS 6b: single-driver addiction overrides topology, analogous to CLASS 6 PTEN-loss mTOR override in GBM).",
