    {
      "id": "h1",
      "label": "ODS Spearman correlation test",
      "statement": "Spearman r(delta_r, mean PRISM LFC) < -0.40 across 5 testable node-drug class pairs (AKT1, PI3K, MEK1, mTOR, BRAF) within BRAF-dependent melanoma lines (BRAF Chronos < -0.5). delta_r range: +0.1263 (AKT1) to -0.2253 (MEK1). If ODS holds in this driver-addicted context, damper nodes (AKT1, PI3K) should have lower LFC (more killing) than anchor nodes (MEK1, mTOR, BRAF)."
    },
    {
      "id": "h2",
      "label": "ODS topology regime test -- AKT1 damper vs MEK1 anchor",
      "statement": "AKT1 mean PRISM LFC < MEK1 mean PRISM LFC in BRAF-dependent melanoma lines. AKT1 is the largest druggable structural damper (delta_r=+0.1263); MEK1 is the largest druggable structural anchor (delta_r=-0.2253). ODS predicts AKT inhibitors should kill more than MEK inhibitors in melanoma. This is the direct ODS regime test for melanoma."
    },
    {
      "id": "h3",
      "label": "Driver addiction override test -- BRAF anchor vs AKT1 damper",
      "statement": "BRAF inhibitor mean PRISM LFC < AKT1 inhibitor mean PRISM LFC in BRAF-dependent melanoma. BRAF is a structural anchor (delta_r=-0.0655) yet targets the V600E driver mutation directly. If BRAF inhibitors kill MORE than AKT1 inhibitors (more negative LFC), this establishes driver mutation addiction overriding topological position (analogous to PTEN-loss mTOR override in GBM). This would define CLASS 6b: single-driver addiction override. If AKT1 kills MORE (H2 confirmed, H3 denied), ODS holds even in driver-addicted context. Reference: vemurafenib clinical response rate ~50% in BRAF V600E melanoma vs mTOR inhibitor modest activity -- strong biological prior favoring H3 confirmation."
    }
